s-do/">·德鲁姆 (Kevin Drum) 有一些证据表明</a>，这种国家与个人的分裂主要是由共和党人推动的： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg" width="1267" height="626" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/da101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:626,&quot;width&quot;:1267,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:94901,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源：昆尼皮亚克大学，作者<a href="https://jabberwocking.com/americans-dont-think-the-economy-is-bad-republicans-do/">：Kevin Drum</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>因此，似乎共和党对国家状态的不满确实是驱动这里大部分负面情绪的原因。如果我被迫猜测，我会说2020年夏天的记忆可能会因为共和党人对民族局势的看法而陷入困境，这使他们感觉好像以前所未有的方式对他们反对他们。</p><h4> 2.中国正在建设军事装备。美国则不然。</h4><p><a href="https://twitter.com/tshugart3/status/1716259376183361842">美国国防部的一份新报告</a>表明，中国的军事积累有多快。</p><p> （首先，不要告诉我，美国在国防上花费的钱比中国要多得多，因为那是不正确的；中国使大部分军事都花在<a href="https://www.aei.org/op-eds/chinas-real-military-budget-is-far-bigger-than-it-looks/">书本上</a>，并且因为他们赚了<a href="https://cepr.org/voxeu/columns/debating-defence-budgets-why-military-purchasing-power-parity-matters">更多的钱</a>。事实上，两国的军费开支可能<a href="https://twitter.com/MEaglen/status/1689283338102616065">大致相等</a>。）</p><p>这是国防分析师汤姆·舒加特（Tom Shugart）的国防部报告的<a href="https://twitter.com/tshugart3/status/1716259376183361842">大细分</a>（<a href="https://twitter.com/tshugart3/status/1716465378635751757">这是第2部分</a>）。基本上，中国正在建造大量的船舶、飞机和导弹。这些是在<a href="https://twitter.com/ianellisjones/status/1718701969093558549">台湾或南中国海战争</a>中与美国作战的武器。它还建立了更多的核武器。</p><p> Shugart线程的一些摘录：</p><blockquote><p> [中华人民共和国通过解放军军事能力的增强，正在对该地区的邻国采取更多的胁迫行动（只要问问菲律宾和台湾就知道了）。 While improving its ability to fight the US, it seems largely uninterested in talking anymore…</p><p> The report puts the PLAN&#39;s hull count at 370 this year, up from 340, and 140 surface combatants, up from 125…That 30-hull jump is more than I expected, as well as the 15-hull jump in surface combatants.我知道他们正在建设，但不知道他们建设得那么快……</p><p>就解放军未来的增长而言，国防部预计到 2025 年将拥有 395 艘舰艇，到 2030 年将达到 435 艘……国防部估计解放军去年已建造了 21 艘元级潜艇，而 2022 年为 17 艘……</p><p> Moving on to the PLA Air Force: this year&#39;s report indicates that the PLAAF now has 1300 4th-gen fighters out of 1900 total (I assume that 1300 includes 5th-gen too), up *500* from the previous year…</p><p> The report shows major increases in every category of China&#39;s long range missiles. Fielded ICBM launchers jump from 300 to 500, and the number of missiles goes up from 300 to 350…While the number of launchers stays the same, the estimate of the number of intermediate-range missiles (ie, the “Guam Killers”) goes从有点模糊的“250+”到可靠的500……</p><p>美国国防部目前估计中国拥有 500 枚核弹头库存，比去年增加了 100 枚。它还将更长的时间表提前至 2030 年“拥有超过 1,000 枚弹头”，而到 2036 年将拥有“约 1,500 枚”弹头。</p></blockquote><p> This is an absolutely astonishing rate of military buildup, and it&#39;s not even wartime. It&#39;s far, far beyond anything the US can manage. China builds 21 submarines a year, while the US struggles to build <em>two</em> . This is <a href="https://www.defensenews.com/naval/2022/01/03/us-navy-avoided-a-2022-trough-in-submarine-fleet-size-but-industry-challenges-threaten-future-growth/">from last year</a> :</p><blockquote><p>即将卸任的特朗普政府随后提出了 72 至 78 艘攻击潜艇的目标，而拜登政府此后<a href="https://sgp.fas.org/crs/weapons/RL32665.pdf">确定了 66 至 72 艘攻击潜艇的范围</a>——除非有什么改变，否则对海军来说仍然遥不可及……</p><p> The industrial base, led by prime contractor General Dynamics Electric Boat and supporting shipbuilder Huntington Ingalls Industries&#39; Newport News Shipbuilding, has struggled to deliver two Virginia-class attack subs a year on schedule.两个船厂各自建造船只的不同部分，然后轮流由谁进行最后的组装和交付。承包商迟迟将一艘又一艘的船交付给海军。</p></blockquote><p> The US defense-industrial base has shriveled to a tiny fraction of what it was in the 1990s. Military analyst Patrick Fox <a href="https://twitter.com/RealCynicalFox/status/1717223315662627033">has this to say</a> :</p><blockquote><p>拜登政府最明显的失败之一是他们拒绝积极进行再工业化以提高我们的武器制造能力。这种必要性在 2022 年变得更加明显，并且在此期间变得更加重要。</p></blockquote><p> He also shows yet more data on how much we&#39;ve struggled just to build artillery shells for Ukraine — a tiny fraction of what we&#39;d need to build for a conflict with China.</p><p> If you&#39;re not worried about this, you should be. You can comfort yourself with the fact that US technology is still a bit better than China&#39;s (maybe), but the World Wars taught us that a huge advantage in quantity is decisive if your technology is decently good. The US is now on the losing end of that asymmetry.这个世界上不再有民主的武库，这个事实应该让你感到困扰。</p><h4> 3. Industrial policy isn&#39;t really about low wages</h4><p> There have been a lot of <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-pushback-against-industrial-policy">sloppy critiques</a> of industrial policy over the last few months, and I&#39;ll go over some more of those in another post soon.但也有一些有趣且明智的批评，我觉得我也应该解决这些问题。例如，<a href="https://www.slowboring.com/p/the-industrial-policy-dilemma">马特·伊格莱西亚斯认为</a>，产业政策将难以创造良好的就业机会，因为它依赖廉价工资作为国际竞争力的来源：</p><blockquote><p> Let&#39;s say you&#39;re a poor country…Then someone, tempted by the low wages in your country, builds a couple of factories….And now as an ongoing matter, his profit margins are really high because the wages are so low. The workers at the factory don&#39;t like that and start talking about…going on strike, and demanding higher pay. What does the government do?…[I]f the government cares about industrial policy and creating a developmental state, it probably <a href="https://pseudoerasmus.com/2017/10/02/ijd/">opts for labor repression and helps break the strike</a> .</p><p>为什么？嗯，因为即使工厂工人的工资过低……国家经济发展的整个战略都是建立在利用这一事实的基础上的……你要做的就是吸引更多的投资，建造更多的工厂，并将更多的工人从农场转移到工业工作中。部门重新分配……是提高工资的策略……</p><p>发展型国家的首选举措是比自由市场<em>更加敌视工人利益</em>……对于像美国这样已经富裕的国家来说，困境在于很难想象一个富裕国家如何才能获得richer by keeping wages low…[D]o you want to do your own <em>industrial policy</em> — wage suppression — to prevent the foreign competition from poaching your industry?</p></blockquote><p> This critique is worth taking seriously, because it&#39;s certainly possible to imagine that excessively high wages will make US industry uncompetitive in international markets. Because their economy is big and <a href="https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NE.EXP.GNFS.ZS">relatively closed-off</a> , Americans are used to thinking only in terms of producing for the domestic market.你可以通过关税等措施保护国内市场。</p><p>但事实上，为<em>世界</em>市场生产极其重要，不仅因为世界市场很大，而且因为为世界生产产品可以推动企业提高生产力水平。因此，在这里你必须具有竞争力，并且不要被中国的竞争严重低估。如果美国工人不断罢工并获得越来越高的工资，最终印度、巴西或德国将没有人愿意购买波音飞机、福特汽车或英特尔半导体； they&#39;ll buy from China instead.</p><p>但从数量上来说，低劳动力成本有多重要？马特引用了<a href="https://pseudoerasmus.com/2017/10/02/ijd/">一些历史研究</a>作为证据，表明日本纺织工业在 20 世纪初通过保持较低的劳动力成本在竞争中击败了印度纺织工业。 But is there any reason to think that example is relevant for the US&#39; situation in the modern day?</p><p> First of all, textile manufacturing at that time was extremely labor-intensive, meaning that labor costs loomed especially large (pun intended) in companies&#39; cost calculations. 2020 年代的高科技制造业，例如半导体行业，是资本密集型产业——制造大量机床，然后为工厂配备知道如何操作这些工具的博士级员工。是的，你需要一些低技能工人来建立、清洁和守卫晶圆厂，并为博士人员提供午餐等。 But these people&#39;s wages are not going to be a big part of the production cost.你所面临的主要劳动力成本主要是你必须支付给超高技能工人的高薪；正如任何科技公司所知，这些工人并不倾向于组建工会并推动工资不断上涨。</p><p>我们特别应该看看中国做对了什么。中国不是全球高科技制造业的中心，因为劳动力成本低； indeed, its labor is <a href="https://www.logisticsmgmt.com/article/global_labor_rates_china_is_no_longer_a_low_cost_country">no longer very cheap</a> , and it <a href="https://www.conference-board.org/publications/China-Competitiveness-Rising-Labor-Unit-Costs">hasn&#39;t been considered</a> a particularly low-cost producer for years now. Instead, China competes based on scale — it&#39;s the only place you can build very large batches of high-tech products very quickly, thanks to its dense networks of suppliers and its huge labor force of well-trained production engineers. Meanwhile, Germany has even higher manufacturing wages than the US, and it&#39;s well-known as a high-tech manufacturing and export powerhouse. </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg" width="777" height="572" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:572,&quot;width&quot;:777,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:80009,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://www.logisticsmgmt.com/article/global_labor_rates_china_is_no_longer_a_low_cost_country">Logistics Management</a> , January 2023</figcaption></figure></div><p> So Matt is formally right that excessively high wages <em>could</em> derail industrial policy, but it&#39;s not clear how much that matters in real life. And Matt certainly isn&#39;t right to equate industrial policy with wage suppression.</p><p>我<em>确实</em>同意马特的观点，他指出了降低土地和监管成本等非工资成本的重要性。但我认为他的批评缺少的是对生产力的考虑。 What&#39;s important for competitiveness isn&#39;t labor cost or land cost or anything else, it&#39;s “ <a href="https://www.bls.gov/k12/productivity-101/content/what-is-productivity/what-is-unit-labor-cost.htm">unit labor cost</a> ” — how much each unit of output costs to produce.公司的生产力越高，其单位劳动力成本就越低，即使其工资确实很高。</p><p>当然，降低土地和监管审批成本是降低单位劳动力成本的重要途径。但改进技术和<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/american-workers-need-lots-and-lots">鼓励自动化也很关键</a>。 The real tradeoff we should be considering when it comes to industrial policy isn&#39;t “wages vs. competitiveness” — it&#39;s “factory job creation vs. competitiveness”. Industrial policy advocates don&#39;t need to accept low wages;他们需要承认，制造业通过促进当地服务的<a href="https://eml.berkeley.edu/~moretti/multipliers.pdf">乘数效应</a>间接创造了良好的就业机会。</p><h4> 4.太阳能利好消息</h4><p>太阳能是您的朋友。它并不是一种比煤炭或核能更软弱、更不男子气概的能源形式。这不是破坏资本主义的嬉皮士阴谋。这并不是一个绝望的后退，让我们靠豆荚生活并吃虫子。 It is <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/dont-be-a-decel">a genuine technological revolution</a> , a modern marvel by which the ingenuity of humankind has harnessed fusion energy from space and turned it directly into pure electric power.</p><p> More importantly, it&#39;s just really really cheap.彭博新能源财经分析师珍妮·蔡斯（Jenny Chase）有<a href="https://twitter.com/solar_chase/status/1718296328676032934">一个很棒的年度主题</a>，她评估了太阳能行业的状况。 Here are a few choice tidbits from this year&#39;s thread.</p><p>许多人曾经声称，我们需要在太阳能电池效率方面取得技术突破，以使太阳能在经济上可行。这从来都不是真的——事实证明我们只需要降低成本——但无论如何，我们确实在不断提高电池效率，而且这些提高会不断增加。蔡斯写道：</p><blockquote><p>太阳能组件的渐进式改进仍在继续。 2023 年，标准设计从 PERC（组件效率约 21.3%）转向 TOPCon（组件效率约 22.3%）。 2023 年太阳能组件的平均效率约为 21.6%，高于 2012 年的 15.4%（现已过时的多晶硅设计）。</p></blockquote><p> That&#39;s a pretty big increase!</p><p>不管怎样，说到成本下降，这种情况一直在发生。 2021年，太阳能成本突然小幅上涨，导致一些人认为学习曲线时代已经结束。但这只是大流行后材料成本暂时上涨的暂时影响。蔡斯指出，成本已经回落：</p><blockquote><p> 2021年10月，当标准单晶组件价格为每瓦27.3美分时，我说它将“在1-2年内回落”（指2020年夏季19美分的历史低点）。 Since it&#39;s now 13.6 US cents in normal markets (ie not the US or India), not too bad a call.</p></blockquote><p> As for whether levelized cost of energy (LCOE) is a good measure of costs, Chase drily notes that it&#39;s pretty much the only measure of cost that matters to utilities on the margin:</p><blockquote><p>顺便说一句，LCOE 只是“你必须向某人支付电力以让他们建造发电厂的价格”的一种奇特说法。</p></blockquote><p>当然，如果你继续建造大量的太阳能，最终间歇性开始变得更加重要。蔡斯解释说，这种间歇性将表现为一天中阳光最充足的时候电价较低甚至为负电价：</p><blockquote><p>继电网和土地问题之后，光伏的下一个重大挑战将是电价蚕食。基本上，一个地区的太阳能发电厂都会同时发电。这意味着他们会降低当时的电价，“蚕食”自己的收入……高太阳能渗透率导致电价蚕食也会影响其他发电厂，但影响程度不如太阳能，因为太阳能发电厂有时发电最多当太阳能将价格压低得最多时。这将抑制进一步的太阳能建设……到 2030 年，大多数国家将在每个晴天的几个小时内实现零现货电价。</p></blockquote><p> Intermittency doesn&#39;t really matter when you only build a modest amount of solar. But when you build an absolutely huge amount, like we&#39;re expected to do in the near future, it starts to bite a lot.但蔡斯乐观地认为，电池将成为解决该问题的一个非常有效的解决方案：</p><blockquote><p>很可能“每个晴天几个小时的负电价，然后是太阳落山后晚上电价高”是资本主义和电池解决的问题……公用事业规模电池的发展速度比我预想的要快得多。 <a href="https://twitter.com/YayoiSekine">@YayoiSekine</a> &#39;s team recorded 16.8GW/32.9GWh of gross energy storage capacity additions worldwide in 2022, and expect 41.9GW/98.6GWh in 2023.</p></blockquote><p> Anti-solar people also claim that solar won&#39;t have enough land to build on. This is probably an issue for wind, but for solar, Chase thinks it&#39;s not that big of a deal:</p><blockquote><p>有足够的土地用于大量太阳能。 There are enough golf courses in the US for about 370GW, ffs. There&#39;s also loads and loads of roofs…</p></blockquote><p> So anyway, that&#39;s all very optimistic stuff, and you should be optimistic too! Solar, together with batteries, looks like the first major step-up transition we&#39;ve gotten in electric power generation technology since the advent of coal itself.</p><h4> 5. What&#39;s destroying the humanities?</h4><p>当有报道称北卡罗来纳大学系统<a href="https://www.wunc.org/education/2023-10-19/unc-system-state-nc-budget-3-7-billion-2023">现在只向 STEM 领域的学者而不是人文学科的教授授予</a>杰出教授职位时，很多人感到不安。一些人<a href="https://twitter.com/RebeccaSpang/status/1717887249679777940">认为这是“美国公立高等教育解体”的标志</a>。 I&#39;m not so sure it means that much, but I do think it&#39;s very likely that the shift away from an emphasis on the humanities will continue. The reason is that undergrads just don&#39;t want to major in these subjects anymore: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg" width="1304" height="806" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:806,&quot;width&quot;:1304,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:154887,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源：<a href="https://twitter.com/benmschmidt/status/1562212497272279041">本·施密特</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>The hard, cold fact is that while professors tend to see themselves as scholars first and educators second, from a university&#39;s perspective, they are primarily <em>instructors</em> ; if there aren&#39;t as many students to instruct, fewer profs are needed.</p><p>为什么人文专业（哲学除外）处于崩溃状态？我对此的典型解释是经济上的——这些学位对于获得高薪工作的用处不大，这就是为什么我们看到学生更多地主修计算机科学、健康、商业和其他实用的东西。 And the timing lines up with the Great Recession, which strongly implies that once economic constraints started to bite, America&#39;s youth became less eager to take a four-year voyage of intellectual pleasure and more focused on grabbing the brass ring.</p><p>但贝茨学院教授泰勒·奥斯汀·哈珀<a href="https://twitter.com/Tyler_A_Harper/status/1717935971985924576">认为</a>，人文学科“赤裸裸的意识形态”是搬起石头砸自己的脚。他写：</p><blockquote><p> [W]我们为北卡罗来纳大学的发展创造了条件。怎么会有人认为我们可以多年来一直赤裸裸的意识形态，而没有任何鸡归巢？……大学一直是心照不宣的左倾，教师也一直是公开的左倾，但机构从来没有像现在这样透明、正式地政治化。 。今年我的领域/相关领域的几乎每一个招聘广告都有某种公然政治化的语言……</p><p>一个例子。以下是当前热门招聘广告的语言：“我们认为这个职位是建立在英语系最近在非殖民和反种族主义教学法和实践方面的招聘以及最近在与多样性、公平和包容性相关的研究方面进行的集群招聘的基础上的。 “……想象一下，如果一则公立大学的招聘广告是这样写的：“我们认为这个职位是建立在英语系最近在传统主义教学法和实践方面的招聘以及最近在与反堕胎伦理、民族主义和文化相关的研究方面的集群招聘的基础上的。家庭价值观。”</p><p> ……这是关于大学无耻地接受公开的意识形态框架/立场作为其官方机构姿态。</p></blockquote><p>让我感到怀疑。 While I do think that conservatives and red-state politicians are very mad at this ideological shift in humanities academia — and I agree with Harper that they have a right to be upset — I doubt that this is driving kids&#39; desire to avoid these majors.选择专业的人是年轻人，而不是共和党政客，而且年轻一代有<em>很多</em>左撇子。 I doubt very much that faculty job descriptions with “diversity, equity, and inclusion” in their names are what&#39;s making kids avoid history and English majors like the plague.</p><p> Instead, my guess is that the ideological shift in humanities academia is more an effect of the sector&#39;s shrinkage than the cause of it.随着人文学术界所有的金钱和机会的枯竭，那些关心过上体面的生活和拥有一份高薪工作的人逐渐远离了这个职业。人文系还剩下谁呢？当然，人们痴迷于自己的研究，但同时也是坚定的空想家。因此，这些理论家将对招聘和整个领域的文化产生越来越大的影响力。</p><p>当然，变得更加意识形态化的人文部门可能更有可能激怒保守派官员进一步削减预算。但我认为人文专业的崩溃必须被视为这种转变的最有可能的罪魁祸首。 So although I&#39;d personally like to see humanities departments be less ideological, I doubt this will save them from decline. The only thing that will save them, I predict, is if the US economy returns to a state in which young people are confident that they can get a good job no matter what they major in.</p><p>因此，基本上，想要拯救自己领域的人文学科教授应该是有利于增长的经济议程的坚定支持者。 </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/at-least-five-interesting-things-ae2?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/at-least-five-interesting-things-ae2?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p>; 
